<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98876003951847></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98876003951847><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=10&mid=98876003951847>RE: A archer's best companion...mages</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=10&mid=98876003951847#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=43653><span id=Scholar>GLASS</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>124 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, May 1st 7:33 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.41]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'll try to clarify the whole magic arrow issue here.&nbsp;&nbsp;Yes, Rangers (or any other fletcher for that matter) can make magic arrows.  Any arrow assembled with a silver tip (I've also senn them referred to as bladed tips I believe) will be magic.  They are extremely expensive as far as arrows go, and are trivial at somewhere above 170, so they are not easy to make either.  Hope this clears up the confusion.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
